431
00:39:00,817 --> 00:39:07,420
Like as far as I can tell, I mean, there was some very early design documents that suggested 14 feet.

432
00:39:08,987 --> 00:39:18,889
I think, but like, as soon as they started actually designing it, they went to 12 and they have completely ignored everything.

433
00:39:19,289 --> 00:39:22,510
And he calls for, um, 14 feet after that.

434
00:39:22,930 --> 00:39:31,112
So that suggests to me that they know the answer to that question, which is that the incremental cost is quite high and it was very quickly value engineered out.

435
00:39:31,172 --> 00:39:36,473
You would think that when you're designing an all new bridge from the start, that surely the difference between like, uh,

436
00:39:37,348 --> 00:39:43,673
12 and 14 or whatever it is, would be a small percentage point difference, but presumably it's much bigger than that otherwise.

